    <a title="Lauren Stoolfire" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6857324-lauren-stoolfire"><img alt="Lauren Stoolfire" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1595823149p2/6857324.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2628996447?book_show_action=true">Feb 24, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lauren Stoolfire" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lauren Stoolfire" href="/user/show/6857324-lauren-stoolfire">Lauren Stoolfire</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6857324-lauren-stoolfire?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2628996447" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13585772487036377024">The same friend who lent me <i>Fifth Avenue: A Very Social History</i> by Kate Simon also let me borrow <i>Obasan</i> by Joy Kogawa and I&apos;m so glad that she did. I wasn&apos;t all that familiar with the Canadian Japanese experience during WWII, but I ended up being quite impressed with Kogawa&apos;s work here. The author&apos;s writing is compelling, beautiful, and incredibly evocative and heartbreaking. I have to admit that I was really pleased with myself for knowing the Japanese words used in the book. Overall, this nove</span>
  <span id="freeText13585772487036377024" style="display:none">The same friend who lent me <i>Fifth Avenue: A Very Social History</i> by Kate Simon also let me borrow <i>Obasan</i> by Joy Kogawa and I'm so glad that she did. I wasn't all that familiar with the Canadian Japanese experience during WWII, but I ended up being quite impressed with Kogawa's work here. The author's writing is compelling, beautiful, and incredibly evocative and heartbreaking. I have to admit that I was really pleased with myself for knowing the Japanese words used in the book. Overall, this novel is a must read for fans of lyrical historical fiction. I need to read <i>Itsuka</i>, the sequel to this novel, soon.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13585772487036377024" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
